01:46.941 --> 01:50.484
and edged weapon specialist,
Doug Marcaida.

01:50.528 --> 01:52.194
Ultimately,
they decide which of you

01:52.238 --> 01:54.196
will be the next
"Forged in Fire" champion,

01:54.240 --> 01:55.781
who also receives
a check for 10 grand.

01:55.825 --> 01:58.200
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

01:58.244 --> 02:00.160
All right, gentlemen.
Let's get started.

02:00.204 --> 02:02.621
I'm sure you're all wondering
what's in front of you.

02:02.665 --> 02:05.666
You will be randomly
choosing one of these boxes.

02:05.709 --> 02:08.919
Each box contains mystery steel
and a specific technique

02:08.963 --> 02:11.004
that you must use
to forge your blade.

02:13.676 --> 02:15.300
Walter, you're up first.

02:15.344 --> 02:17.386
Please choose your box.

02:17.429 --> 02:23.684
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:23.727 --> 02:27.479
Walter, you've chosen
canister Damascus.

02:27.523 --> 02:30.149
<i> - I've done canister Damascus</i>
<i> in the past.</i>

02:30.192 --> 02:32.276
It's horrible.

02:32.319 --> 02:34.528
<i> As a smith, this is really</i>
<i> one of the most</i>

02:34.572 --> 02:37.072
technically difficult things
that you can do.

02:38.868 --> 02:40.576
- Theo, you're up next.

02:40.619 --> 02:45.205
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:45.249 --> 02:46.540
You have chosen
the hada technique.

02:46.584 --> 02:48.709
- All right.

02:48.752 --> 02:51.295
<i> I see that it's steel</i>
<i> that I've worked with before,</i>

02:51.338 --> 02:53.714
and it's just such a relief
to know immediately,

02:53.757 --> 02:56.550
"Okay, I can do this."

02:56.594 --> 02:58.010
- Joe, you're up next.

02:58.053 --> 02:59.720
Please choose your box.

02:59.763 --> 03:01.722
- [sighs]

03:01.765 --> 03:04.558
<i> There are two boxes left,</i>
<i> so it's 50/50.</i>

03:04.602 --> 03:06.685
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

03:06.729 --> 03:08.395
- You got some good vibes
from that one, right?

03:08.439 --> 03:09.646
- Good vibes.
- All right.

03:09.690 --> 03:12.024
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

03:12.067 --> 03:14.484
Joe, you've chosen Damascus.

03:14.528 --> 03:16.486
- Damascus?
All right, I can do this.

03:16.530 --> 03:18.614
I know what the metal is.
I know the process.

03:18.657 --> 03:20.949
This is awesome.

03:20.993 --> 03:22.659
- Erich, you're last.

03:22.703 --> 03:27.581
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

03:27.625 --> 03:30.459
You have chosen the metal
inlay technique.

03:30.502 --> 03:32.711
- Inlay technique?

03:32.755 --> 03:35.672
That's a difficult job
right there.

03:35.716 --> 03:37.466
- All right, gents,
keep in mind that in round two,

03:37.509 --> 03:39.551
you'll be attaching handles
to your blades

03:39.595 --> 03:41.637
to turn them into
fully-functional weapons

03:41.680 --> 03:44.806
that will then be tested
in a tatami mat slice

03:44.850 --> 03:47.100
and a bone marrow chop.

03:47.144 --> 03:49.102
You will have ten minutes
to work on your design,

03:49.146 --> 03:51.480
three hours
to forge your blades.

03:51.523 --> 03:54.191
Do your best work
because when the time runs out,

03:54.235 --> 03:56.985
one of you will have
to surrender his blade

03:57.029 --> 03:59.112
and leave the Forge.

03:59.156 --> 04:02.115
Your ten-minute design
window starts...now.

04:02.159 --> 04:05.035
<i> [rock music]</i>

04:05.079 --> 04:06.745
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:06.789 --> 04:08.997
<i>- When cutting the tatami mats,</i>

04:09.041 --> 04:11.166
working on that edge shape,
what kind of blade--

04:11.210 --> 04:13.252
curve or flat blade,
what do you want to see?

04:13.295 --> 04:15.254
- I'm one that likes curves.
- Mm-hmm.

04:15.297 --> 04:16.797
<i> - To cut through mat</i>
<i> and the bone,</i>

04:16.840 --> 04:18.632
I'm gonna need the weight
in my spine,

04:18.676 --> 04:20.259
and I'm gonna need
a good handle,

04:20.302 --> 04:23.011
<i> so I'm starting out</i>
<i> with a hybrid</i>

04:23.055 --> 04:25.681
<i> between a kukri</i>
<i> and a bowie style.</i>

04:25.724 --> 04:28.517
I think that this is gonna be
my best bet to get through.

04:28.560 --> 04:31.687
<i> The inlay technique is...</i>
<i> difficult.</i>

04:31.730 --> 04:33.438
<i> I'm gonna have to bring</i>

04:33.482 --> 04:35.190
<i> two pieces of steel together,</i>

04:35.234 --> 04:37.734
<i> leave my harder metal</i>
<i> as my edge,</i>

04:37.778 --> 04:40.237
<i> and the softer spine</i>
<i>is gonna be the standard steel.</i>

04:40.281 --> 04:42.447
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:42.491 --> 04:45.701
- It looks like Theo has
designed a competition cleaver.

04:45.744 --> 04:47.494
- I've seen
the competition cleavers

04:47.538 --> 04:49.788
do very well
in just a straight laser edge.

04:49.832 --> 04:51.707
<i> - I'm going to make a macheax,</i>

04:51.750 --> 04:53.875
<i> which is a blend</i>
<i> of a machete and sax.</i>

04:53.919 --> 04:55.627
<i> It's meant to go through bone,</i>

04:55.671 --> 04:57.379
but it's also lightweight enough

04:57.423 --> 04:59.756
to take with you
into the forest.

04:59.800 --> 05:01.842
With the hada technique,
the first thing is

05:01.885 --> 05:03.927
<i> tack weld</i>
<i> all these pieces together.</i>

05:03.971 --> 05:05.345
<i> From there,</i>
<i> I'm gonna draw it out</i>

05:05.389 --> 05:06.763
<i> and start flattening it</i>

05:06.807 --> 05:08.849
<i> to try and get</i>
<i> a distinct pattern.</i>

05:08.892 --> 05:11.685
Okay, yeah.
Exactly where I want it.

05:11.729 --> 05:13.395
- I gotta chop through a mat,

05:13.439 --> 05:15.147
<i> and I gotta chop</i>
<i> through some bone,</i>

05:15.190 --> 05:17.232
<i> and so I'm thinking kind of</i>
<i> a chopper-style</i>

05:17.276 --> 05:19.609
<i> for some</i>
<i> sort of kukri-type design.</i>

05:19.653 --> 05:21.486
I have a really long blade, and
I'm gonna hack through stuff,

05:21.530 --> 05:23.739
so it's a drop-point hacker.

05:23.782 --> 05:25.574
<i> The easiest way</i>
<i> to make Damascus</i>

05:25.617 --> 05:27.576
<i> is weld all the pieces</i>
<i> together,</i>

05:27.619 --> 05:29.369
<i> and then you got to fold it,</i>

05:29.413 --> 05:31.079
<i> cut it apart,</i>
<i> fold it again,</i>

05:31.123 --> 05:32.414
<i> cut it apart, fold it again,</i>

05:32.458 --> 05:34.958
<i> and make a blade.</i>

05:35.002 --> 05:36.585
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:36.628 --> 05:38.837
- My experience as a bladesmith

05:38.881 --> 05:40.964
is mostly
in Japanese sword realms,

05:41.008 --> 05:44.676
<i> so I'm gonna make</i>
<i> a Japanese-style wakizashi.</i>

05:44.720 --> 05:47.512
<i> This kind of knife</i>
<i> will cut cow bones</i>

05:47.556 --> 05:49.431
really effectively.

05:49.475 --> 05:51.725
- Of all these techniques,
the ones I've seen go wrong

05:51.769 --> 05:54.436
most often is probably canister.

05:54.480 --> 05:57.397
<i> - With canister Damascus,</i>
<i> you're making a billet,</i>

05:57.441 --> 06:01.318
<i> but it's inside of this</i>
<i> very thick-walled steel tube.</i>

06:01.362 --> 06:03.653
<i> The steel tube</i>
<i> is not part of your knife.</i>

06:03.697 --> 06:06.114
<i>It just has to go away somehow.</i>

06:06.158 --> 06:07.866
<i> Cut the canister off</i>

06:07.910 --> 06:11.203
<i> and start</i>
<i> just pulling that billet out.</i>

06:11.246 --> 06:13.580
- Bladesmiths, your ten-minute
design window is closed.

06:13.624 --> 06:14.956
Your three-hour forge time

06:15.000 --> 06:18.502
starts...now.

06:18.545 --> 06:21.671
- All right.
- And they're off.

06:21.715 --> 06:23.590
- Time starts now.

06:23.634 --> 06:24.966
Oh, no.
[chuckling]

06:25.010 --> 06:26.385
<i> [stammers]</i>
<i> What just happened?</i>

06:26.428 --> 06:27.719
<i> What am I doing?</i>
<i> Where are we?</i>

06:27.763 --> 06:29.596
- Whoo...
both: Let's do it.

06:29.640 --> 06:32.265
- So Joe's got
the standard Damascus.

06:32.309 --> 06:34.643
Walter has
the canister Damascus.

06:34.686 --> 06:37.020
Erich has the inlay technique.

06:37.064 --> 06:38.647
Theo's got the hada,

06:38.690 --> 06:41.900
and to watch
how each smith engages

06:41.944 --> 06:44.403
his individual technique
that he drew,

06:44.446 --> 06:47.614
that's exciting stuff.
- All righty then.

06:47.658 --> 06:50.200
<i> The hada doesn't require</i>
<i> any immediate prep work,</i>

06:50.244 --> 06:54.037
so I'm gonna really
start off fast and hard

06:54.081 --> 06:56.706
and maybe psyche these guys out
a little bit.

06:56.750 --> 06:58.708
- Theo's already started
to weld up his billet.

06:58.752 --> 07:03.922
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:03.966 --> 07:05.674
Walter has the liquid paper.

07:05.717 --> 07:08.176
He's pouring on the inside
of that canister.

07:08.220 --> 07:11.430
<i> - Liquid paper is great</i>
<i> because it keeps the canister</i>

07:11.473 --> 07:14.349
from welding to the billet
that you make.

07:14.393 --> 07:15.434
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:15.477 --> 07:17.144
Ah, what am I doing?

07:17.187 --> 07:20.272
<i> That makes it easier</i>
<i> to knock that can off.</i>

07:20.315 --> 07:21.815
- The main thing with lining
with the liquid paper

07:21.859 --> 07:23.567
is to be consistent.

07:23.610 --> 07:26.862
Get it nice and even
and everything covered.

07:26.905 --> 07:29.489
- There are just a lot
of potential problems

07:29.533 --> 07:31.408
in getting
that tube off of there.

07:31.452 --> 07:33.368
Going hot here.

07:33.412 --> 07:35.745
<i> So I know that I've gotta</i>
<i> really stay focused</i>

07:35.789 --> 07:38.457
and not waste
one second of time.

07:38.500 --> 07:39.958
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:40.002 --> 07:42.586
<i> - Okay,</i>
<i> I need to make Damascus.</i>

07:42.629 --> 07:45.130
I got to get as many layers
in as possible.

07:45.174 --> 07:48.008
The more layers I can put it in,
the stronger, the sharper,

07:48.051 --> 07:49.759
the harder it's gonna be.

07:49.803 --> 07:52.387
I believe that those
that excel in life

07:52.431 --> 07:56.600
exceed what normal people
refuse to do.

07:56.643 --> 07:58.226
<i> I don't think I'm normal.</i>

07:58.270 --> 08:00.437
I think
I'm an exceptional person.

08:00.481 --> 08:03.064
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:03.108 --> 08:04.649
<i> - This is gonna be</i>
<i> my first time</i>

08:04.693 --> 08:08.487
doing this inlay technique
on a long blade.

08:08.530 --> 08:11.573
<i> The inlay technique</i>
<i> is difficult.</i>

08:11.617 --> 08:13.116
I'm gonna have to bring

08:13.160 --> 08:15.952
two pieces of steel together.

08:15.996 --> 08:18.330
Right now I'm splitting
the billet down the middle

08:18.373 --> 08:20.999
so I can open it up enough
to get a good surface

08:21.043 --> 08:22.834
to forge weld

08:22.878 --> 08:26.463
my hardening edge onto.

08:26.507 --> 08:28.215
- That's probably
the most difficult way

08:28.258 --> 08:30.008
to do this type of weld.

08:30.052 --> 08:32.052
It'd be best

08:32.095 --> 08:34.554
if he had stretched
that piece of mild steel out,

08:34.598 --> 08:35.972
cut it in half,

08:36.016 --> 08:37.641
stuck his high carbon
in the middle,

08:37.684 --> 08:39.851
and then forge weld
that all together.

08:39.895 --> 08:41.478
- I don't know.
I don't like the timeframe

08:41.522 --> 08:43.104
where I'm at just starting
my split right now,

08:43.148 --> 08:45.815
but...it will come.

08:45.859 --> 08:48.276
- You have just
two hours remaining

08:48.320 --> 08:49.986
to finish your blades.

08:50.030 --> 08:53.240
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:53.283 --> 08:54.991
- Easy-peasy lemon-squeezy.

08:55.035 --> 08:57.035
<i> For the hada technique,</i>

08:57.079 --> 08:58.745
<i> drawing out the billet's</i>
<i> probably the easiest part</i>

08:58.789 --> 09:00.413
and honestly the most fun

09:00.457 --> 09:02.624
'cause I get to work
on that power hammer.

09:02.668 --> 09:04.584
<i> And I know my expression</i>
<i> might be serious,</i>

09:04.628 --> 09:07.754
but the reality is, inside,
I am partying the whole time.

09:07.798 --> 09:08.964
It's great.

09:09.007 --> 09:10.924
I'm having a blast.
[laughs]

09:10.968 --> 09:12.592
I think humor's
really important.

09:12.636 --> 09:15.303
You can disarm people
with humor.

09:15.347 --> 09:17.389
My favorite bladesmith joke is

09:17.432 --> 09:19.724
bladesmith walks into
a lingerie bar.

09:19.768 --> 09:21.226
Lingerie bar?
What the [bleep]?

09:21.270 --> 09:22.310
Okay, hold on...
[clears throat]

09:22.354 --> 09:23.770
Excuse me one second.

09:23.814 --> 09:26.856
Blacksmith walks into
a lingerie store.

09:26.900 --> 09:27.857
No, that's not it.

09:27.901 --> 09:29.150
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:29.194 --> 09:30.360
Hmm.

09:30.404 --> 09:32.320
Blacksmith walks in--

09:32.364 --> 09:35.073
no, that's not how it goes,
[bleep]damn it.

09:35.117 --> 09:38.368
Why did the blacksmith
walk into the lingerie store?

09:38.412 --> 09:41.079
He heard there was a sale
on designer tongs.

09:41.123 --> 09:43.081
[laughs softly]

09:43.125 --> 09:44.583
Most fun I've had in a forge
in a long time.

09:44.626 --> 09:46.918
[machine thumping]

09:46.962 --> 09:48.545
<i> - I draw up the billet.</i>

09:48.589 --> 09:50.547
I get it to a decent size.

09:50.591 --> 09:53.133
Cut that thing up.

09:53.176 --> 09:55.468
<i> There's 36 layers right now.</i>

09:55.512 --> 09:56.678
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:56.722 --> 09:58.555
It's not enough.

09:58.599 --> 10:02.183
<i> I need something</i>
<i> that's gonna distinguish this.</i>

10:02.227 --> 10:05.562
I'm designing
a ladder pattern Damascus.

10:05.606 --> 10:07.230
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

10:07.274 --> 10:09.107
- Joe over here is
drawing out his billet,

10:09.151 --> 10:10.525
looking really good.

