to weld
those two things together.

13:05.702 --> 13:06.826
- Cool.
If he wants to do that

13:06.870 --> 13:08.578
and then forge weld it.
Cool.

13:08.622 --> 13:10.497
<i> - All I'm focused on</i>
<i> right now is</i>

13:10.540 --> 13:13.082
making this blade usable.

13:13.126 --> 13:14.834
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

13:14.878 --> 13:16.669
- You have 15 minutes

13:16.713 --> 13:19.923
to turn in
fully-hardened blades!

13:19.966 --> 13:25.678
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

13:25.722 --> 13:28.765
- Coming along.
Coming along.

13:28.809 --> 13:30.391
So once I've got the blade

13:30.435 --> 13:33.019
<i> ground close enough</i>
<i> for rock and roll,</i>

13:33.063 --> 13:35.313
<i> I'm ready to heat-treat it.</i>

13:35.357 --> 13:39.234
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

13:39.277 --> 13:41.027
- Look at Erich's blade
over here.

13:41.071 --> 13:44.030
Kicking out sparks
like nobody's business.

13:44.074 --> 13:47.325
He's trying to make up time.

13:47.369 --> 13:50.161
Theo's got
a nasty chopper right there.

13:50.205 --> 13:52.831
Look at that thing.
- And he's going for a hamon.

13:52.874 --> 13:56.543
- I think doing a hamon
right now is a mistake.

13:56.586 --> 13:58.169
There's not a lot of time left.

13:58.213 --> 14:00.338
His best strategy would be

14:00.382 --> 14:02.882
to harden the blade.

14:02.926 --> 14:05.468
- I look over at my competitor.
I'm like, "Oh, man.

14:05.512 --> 14:07.595
He's doing hamon.
Theo's doing--

14:07.639 --> 14:09.472
man, he's doing hamon."

