I gotta do something,
so I go, "Where's the clay?"

14:11.434 --> 14:13.476
<i> So I grab the clay, I slather</i>
<i> it on there as quick as I can.</i>

14:13.520 --> 14:17.105
- Joe's gonna have
a ladder pattern Damascus

14:17.148 --> 14:18.773
with a hamon line.

14:18.817 --> 14:20.525
- Pointless,
and I don't like it.

14:20.569 --> 14:22.777
When you spend this
much time making Damascus,

14:22.821 --> 14:27.740
I really would prefer just to
see the steel all cleaned off.

14:27.784 --> 14:29.951
- Joe in the quench.

14:29.995 --> 14:32.036
Theo in the quench.

14:32.080 --> 14:33.538
- And Walter in the quench.
- Walter--

14:33.582 --> 14:34.747
- Walter in the quench.
- Bang, bang, bang.

14:34.791 --> 14:36.332
- We got three bladesmiths

14:36.376 --> 14:38.459
almost quenched simultaneously.

14:38.503 --> 14:42.422
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

14:42.465 --> 14:49.596
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

14:49.639 --> 14:51.723
- [laughing]

14:51.766 --> 14:53.641
This clay doesn't want
to come off,

14:53.685 --> 14:55.059
and it's fighting me.

14:55.103 --> 14:57.353
<i> It's really stuck on there.</i>

14:57.397 --> 14:59.606
Ah, [bleep].
- It's a good-looking blade.

14:59.649 --> 15:01.524
I want the clay off of it.

15:01.568 --> 15:04.944
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

15:04.988 --> 15:06.988
- There we go.
Erich is in.

15:07.032 --> 15:08.615
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

15:08.658 --> 15:12.076
Boom.

15:12.120 --> 15:15.079
<i> - Looking at my blade,</i>
<i> and I got this little kink.</i>

15:15.123 --> 15:16.289
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

15:16.333 --> 15:18.875
Heart kinda sinks.

15:18.919 --> 15:21.794
I can fix it,
but I'm running out of time.

15:21.838 --> 15:24.881
- He's making a three point.
He's got a bend.

15:24.925 --> 15:27.425
- Not a good time to do it.
- [shouting] Ten, nine,

15:27.469 --> 15:30.219
eight, seven, six,

15:30.263 --> 15:32.180
five, four,

15:32.223 --> 15:35.183
three, two, one!

15:35.226 --> 15:37.560
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines!

15:37.604 --> 15:38.937
Drop your tools!

15:38.980 --> 15:41.940
- [bleep] A.
- Whoo.

15:41.983 --> 15:44.192
<i> - I know that there are</i>
<i> some occlusions in the blade,</i>

15:44.235 --> 15:48.071
and I am concerned that
they're gonna judge on them,

15:48.114 --> 15:50.615
uh, not on the functionality
of the weapon.

15:50.659 --> 15:52.909
- I look left and I look right,
and I'm like,

15:52.953 --> 15:55.370
"Straight, straight, straight.
Hard, hard, hard.

15:55.413 --> 15:57.121
Crooked."

15:57.165 --> 15:58.998
<i> I got a bent blade.</i>
<i> I got a bent handle.</i>

15:59.042 --> 16:01.918
Only way I can fix it is
if I move on to the next round.

16:01.962 --> 16:04.837
<i> I don't know</i>
<i> if that's gonna happen.</i>

16:04.881 --> 16:07.131
- Bladesmiths,
now it's time for the judges

16:07.175 --> 16:08.508
to critique your work.

16:08.551 --> 16:10.385
Erich, you're up first.

16:10.428 --> 16:13.638
Please present your blade
to the judges.

16:13.682 --> 16:16.307
<i> - What I'm most impressed with</i>
<i> is how you finally figured out</i>

16:16.351 --> 16:19.394
how to get that hard steel
stuck to the soft steel.

16:19.437 --> 16:21.229
So you did well
in that situation.

16:21.272 --> 16:23.481
- Thank you.
- There are a couple of spots

16:23.525 --> 16:24.732
<i> here that I'm a little bit</i>
<i> concerned about,</i>

16:24.776 --> 16:26.859
<i> but it's not separating,</i>

16:26.903 --> 16:29.237
so I'm hoping that those welds
under there are nice and tight.

16:29.280 --> 16:31.572
All in all, good shape.
Well done.

16:31.616 --> 16:33.116
- Walter, you're up.

16:33.159 --> 16:34.450
Please present your blade
to the judges.

16:34.494 --> 16:36.661
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

16:36.705 --> 16:39.163
<i> - One of the things we love</i>
<i> about the canister Damascus</i>

16:39.207 --> 16:41.416
is that it brings out
this beautiful pattern

16:41.459 --> 16:42.917
<i> that you have right here</i>

16:42.961 --> 16:45.586
and, of course, feels good.

16:45.630 --> 16:47.046
Excellent job, sir.

16:47.090 --> 16:48.798
- Thank you.
- Joe, you're up.

16:48.842 --> 16:50.800
Please present your work
to the judges.

16:50.844 --> 16:53.428
<i> - Joe, one of the things</i>
<i> that I thought was cool</i>

16:53.471 --> 16:55.638
<i>is that you took that Damascus,</i>

16:55.682 --> 16:57.015
you got it forge welded,
and then you cut

16:57.058 --> 16:59.017
a ladder pattern into it.

16:59.060 --> 17:02.103
One thing I didn't understand
was why you put clay on it.

17:02.147 --> 17:03.771
I think that clay
is one of the reasons

17:03.815 --> 17:05.606
you got this severe warp

17:05.650 --> 17:08.526
right here at the junction
between your blade and handle.

17:08.570 --> 17:10.361
<i> But overall,</i>
<i> the steel looks great.</i>

17:10.405 --> 17:11.571
Well done.
- Thank you.

17:11.614 --> 17:13.823
It was quite a challenge.

17:13.867 --> 17:15.116
- Theo, you're up.

17:15.160 --> 17:17.660
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

17:17.704 --> 17:19.746
<i> - You were kind of</i>
<i> making me crazy there</i>

17:19.789 --> 17:21.039
<i> when you were putting</i>
<i> the clay on it.</i>

17:21.082 --> 17:23.541
- [sighs]
Yeah, I way over-clayed it.

17:23.585 --> 17:25.752
- It looks like you got
barnacles growing on it,

17:25.795 --> 17:28.254
so hopefully you will figure out
how to get that off.

17:28.298 --> 17:31.466
<i> Your steel looks good.</i>
<i>I don't see any issues with it.</i>

17:31.509 --> 17:33.426
You did well.
- Thank you.

17:33.470 --> 17:35.053
- Bladesmiths, the judges are
gonna have to take

17:35.096 --> 17:36.637
a closer look at your work

17:36.681 --> 17:38.973
to determine who moves on
to the next round.

17:39.017 --> 17:40.850
Please leave your blades here
on the table

17:40.894 --> 17:43.269
and step off the Forge floor.
Thank you.

17:43.313 --> 17:48.357
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

17:48.401 --> 17:51.235
- Man, that flat
kicked my ass.

17:51.279 --> 17:54.864
- The challenge
was unbelievably hard.

17:54.908 --> 17:57.992
- We'll start with Theo's blade.

17:58.036 --> 17:59.952
<i> - There's a lot of crud</i>
<i> on this thing,</i>

17:59.996 --> 18:03.164
but I don't see any cracks that
travel either through the spine

18:03.208 --> 18:05.166
or through the front
of the edge,

18:05.210 --> 18:07.960
so I have a feeling
it's pretty well welded up.

18:08.004 --> 18:10.671
I like the shape--this is more
of a competition cutter.

18:10.715 --> 18:12.256
It's a little longer.

18:12.300 --> 18:14.592
Should be a pretty good,
uh, performer.

18:14.636 --> 18:16.344
- All right, let's move on
to Joe's blade.

18:16.387 --> 18:18.137
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

18:18.181 --> 18:21.265
<i> - Biggest problem here</i>
<i> is this tremendous warp</i>

18:21.309 --> 18:22.850
right here
at the blade-handle junction.

18:22.894 --> 18:25.103
Now, that can be fixed

18:25.146 --> 18:27.522
if he has the skill set
to do so.

18:27.565 --> 18:29.607
I hope he does it
without breaking his blade,

18:29.651 --> 18:31.234
but if he does, he does.

18:31.277 --> 18:33.569
- All right.
Let's move on to Walter's blade.

18:33.613 --> 18:35.822
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

18:35.865 --> 18:37.448
<i> - You can see that he's got</i>
<i> his Japanese-style influence</i>

18:37.492 --> 18:39.367
of making the blade.

18:39.410 --> 18:42.495
Can't get over the beautiful
finish and pattern

18:42.539 --> 18:43.871
he's got out of his canister.

18:43.915 --> 18:45.373
Very impressive.

18:45.416 --> 18:46.916
- And last is Erich's ble.

18:46.960 --> 18:48.835
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

18:48.878 --> 18:51.420
<i> - I just--I worry about this,</i>
<i> the construction.</i>

18:51.464 --> 18:54.507
We don't know how much metal
he got sleeved in.

18:54.551 --> 18:56.175
I mean, it wasn't very deep.

18:56.219 --> 18:58.094
<i> You can see the track</i>
<i> of that weld.</i>

18:58.138 --> 19:00.596
<i> We don't know</i>
<i> what's underneath that,</i>

19:00.640 --> 19:01.973
and if he does
grind down deep enough

19:02.016 --> 19:03.641
to lose these as surface cracks,

19:03.685 --> 19:06.102
he might be opening up a weld

19:06.146 --> 19:08.604
that's not true
all the way through that blade.

19:08.648 --> 19:10.648
- All right, judges, have you
made your final decision?

19:10.692 --> 19:11.858
Doug.
- Yes, I have.

19:11.901 --> 19:12.859
- Dave?
- Yes, I have.

19:12.902 --> 19:14.193
- Jason?
- Yeah, man.

19:14.237 --> 19:15.278
- All right,
let's go tell our smiths.

19:15.321 --> 19:18.573
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

19:18.616 --> 19:21.033
The judges have completed
their deliberation,

19:21.077 --> 19:23.077
and they've made
a final decision.

19:23.121 --> 19:24.620
It's time for one of you...

